Ok I solved it by using an array of HWND instead like this
`HWND window[100];`

    for(int i = 0; i &lt; 30; i++) {
        window[i] = CreateWindowW(L&quot;static&quot;, L&quot;Test&quot;, WS_VISIBLE | WS_CHILD, 40, 
        i * 50, 100, 50, hWnd, NULL, NULL, NULL);
    }

    //removing child windows
    for(int i = 0; i &lt; 30; i++) {
        DestroyWindow(window[i]);
    }

You are using the uninitialized pointer ```HWND *window;``` which is causing the access violation and using an array of 100 handles to fix the problem is not a good idea for a few reasons:

- You are only using 30 out of 100 handles
- You are statically allocating the handles

A better option would be to malloc your window handle array:
```
int window_amount = 30;

HWND *window = malloc(sizeof(HWND)*window_amount);

//adding child windows
for(int i = 0; i &lt; window_amount; i++) {
    window[i] = CreateWindowW(L&quot;static&quot;, L&quot;Test&quot;, WS_VISIBLE | WS_CHILD, 40, 
    i * 50, 100, 50, hWnd, NULL, NULL, NULL);
    window++;
}

//removing child windows
for(int i = 0; i &lt; window_amount; i++) {
    DestroyWindow(window[i]);
    window--;
}
```

