answers.body_markdown:
**Note:** The below answer is using an example for AWS, though all of should apply to Azure as well, using its own keywords.

The common practice is to generate images from Packer suffixed with some sort of version, such as a timestamp:

    &quot;ami_name&quot;: &quot;my-packer-image-{{timestamp}}&quot;

Then, at Terraform, a data source is defined to retrieve the image with a wildcard that matches all the versions along with the `most_recent` property set to `true`, like so:

    data &quot;aws_ami&quot; &quot;myimage&quot; {
      most_recent = true

      filter {
        name   = &quot;name&quot;
        values = [&quot;my-packer-image-*&quot;]
      }

      owners = [&quot;&lt;aws-account-id-goes-here&gt;&quot;]
    }

The instance will then be declared referencing this data source:

    resource &quot;aws_instance&quot; &quot;myinstance&quot; {
      ami           = &quot;${data.aws_ami.myimage.id}&quot; 
      instance_type = &quot;t2.micro&quot;
    }

When Packer rebuilds the image and creates a new one, with a new timestamp, thanks to the data source Terraform will be able to detect the new image version and will rebuild the instance again with that new image.

For the specific case of Azure, [azurerm_image](https://www.terraform.io/docs/providers/azurerm/d/image.html) data source has a `name_regex` and `sort_descending` attributes available, that should allow you to achieve the same result. While choosing the version to use, bear in mind that Azure `sort_descending` is based on name and not on a date, which might affect what it considers the first.

